<paragraph blockId="100.[151,1437,795,1434]" box="[199,1132,1155,1182]" pageId="100" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,300,1155,1182]" pageId="100" pageNumber="101">Habitat:</emphasis>
Sagebrush steppe shrub and grassland vegetation 
<typeStatus box="[863,915,1156,1182]" pageId="100" pageNumber="101">type</typeStatus>
. Rangeland breaks.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="100.[151,1437,795,1434]" pageId="100" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,316,1192,1218]" pageId="100" pageNumber="101">Ethology:</emphasis>
Rests on and forages from sand, small rocks, fallen logs, dead roots, and sticks. Mated pair, backside of Casper Mt., 
<date box="[321,470,1228,1254]" pageId="100" pageNumber="101" value="1972-05-17">17 May 1972</date>
(
<collectionCode box="[486,538,1228,1254]" pageId="100" pageNumber="101">RJL</collectionCode>
), in the tail-to-tail position, 12 noon-sunny, soil surface temperature 21.1ºC (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Lavigne, R. J." box="[151,310,1263,1290]" pageId="100" pageNumber="101" pagination="337 - 342" refId="ref104717" refString="Lavigne, R. J. (1971) Backomyia seminoensis sp. n. from Wyoming with ethological notes on B. limpidipennis. Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society, 44, 337 - 342" type="journal article" year="1971">Lavigne 1971</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
